 {"id": "franken_networkx-domtype", "title": "REVIEW: [MEDIUM] dominating_set returned list; nx (and fnx's own docstring) says set", "description": "nx.dominating_set returns a Python set. The Rust binding returned a list. The docstring already claimed set, so users doing set ops (issubset, intersection, union) on the result silently broke. Coerce the Rust return to set when the native path is used; the nx-parity delegation branch already returns a set.", "status": "closed", "priority": 3, "issue_type": "bug", "created_at": "2026-04-24T14:30:00.000000000Z", "created_by": "cc-networkx", "updated_at": "2026-04-24T14:30:00.000000000Z", "closed_at": "2026-04-24T14:30:00.000000000Z", "close_reason": "Coerce to set on native path", "source_repo": ".", "compaction_level": 0, "original_size": 0}
 {"id": "franken_networkx-wlhash", "title": "REVIEW: [MEDIUM] weisfeiler_lehman_graph_hash produced different hashes than nx for the same graph", "description": "fnx's local WL implementation seeded initial labels with str(degree) and hashed with blake2b, while nx's scheme seeds empty (or node_attr) with a different multiset hashing strategy that changed in nx v3.5. Hashes diverged for the same graph+args, so fnx and nx cannot be used interchangeably as graph fingerprinters. Delegate to nx for exact parity.", "status": "closed", "priority": 3, "issue_type": "bug", "created_at": "2026-04-24T14:30:00.000000000Z", "created_by": "cc-networkx", "updated_at": "2026-04-24T14:30:00.000000000Z", "closed_at": "2026-04-24T14:30:00.000000000Z", "close_reason": "Delegate to nx", "source_repo": ".", "compaction_level": 0, "original_size": 0}
 {"id": "franken_networkx-wlsubhash", "title": "REVIEW: [HIGH] weisfeiler_lehman_subgraph_hashes missing include_initial_labels kwarg + wrong output", "description": "nx.weisfeiler_lehman_subgraph_hashes has a ``include_initial_labels=False`` kwarg (default False). fnx's signature was missing that kwarg entirely AND the implementation unconditionally prepended the initial-label hash to each node's list, yielding iterations+1 hashes per node vs nx's iterations. Also used a different internal hashing scheme so even the hash strings differed. Delegate to nx so signature, length, and hash values all match.", "status": "closed", "priority": 2, "issue_type": "bug", "created_at": "2026-04-24T14:30:00.000000000Z", "created_by": "cc-networkx", "updated_at": "2026-04-24T14:30:00.000000000Z", "closed_at": "2026-04-24T14:30:00.000000000Z", "close_reason": "Add kwarg + delegate to nx", "source_repo": ".", "compaction_level": 0, "original_size": 0}
+{"id": "franken_networkx-myciel01", "title": "REVIEW: [MEDIUM] mycielski_graph off-by-one at small n (n=0 and n=1 wrong)", "description": "nx.mycielski_graph(0) raises NetworkXError('must satisfy n >= 1') and nx.mycielski_graph(1) returns the single-vertex graph (1 node, 0 edges). fnx's implementation started from complete_graph(2) and iterated n-2 times, so it returned K2 (2 nodes, 1 edge) for both n=0 and n=1 \u2014 diverging from nx at the base of the sequence. Added explicit handling: n<1 raises nx-exact message; n==1 returns a 1-node graph with no edges; n>=2 falls through to the existing iteration.", "status": "closed", "priority": 3, "issue_type": "bug", "created_at": "2026-04-24T14:45:00.000000000Z", "created_by": "cc-networkx", "updated_at": "2026-04-24T14:45:00.000000000Z", "closed_at": "2026-04-24T14:45:00.000000000Z", "close_reason": "Explicit small-n branches", "source_repo": ".", "compaction_level": 0, "original_size": 0}
+{"id": "franken_networkx-ringlabels", "title": "REVIEW: [HIGH] ring_of_cliques used string node labels like '0_0'; nx uses contiguous integers", "description": "The Rust ring_of_cliques binding emitted nodes as strings ('0_0', '0_1', '1_0', ...), which is a complete labelling divergence from nx's canonical 0..num_cliques*clique_size-1 integer labels. Users comparing edge sets or doing isinstance(n, int) downstream silently broke. Also the error messages for num_cliques<2 / clique_size<2 used internal parameter names rather than nx's human wording. Shadowed the Rust binding with a Python wrapper that mirrors nx's algorithm exactly (combinations over consecutive integer ranges + a bridge edge at i*k+1 to (i+1)*k % total) and uses nx's exact error messages.", "status": "closed", "priority": 2, "issue_type": "bug", "created_at": "2026-04-24T14:45:00.000000000Z", "created_by": "cc-networkx", "updated_at": "2026-04-24T14:45:00.000000000Z", "closed_at": "2026-04-24T14:45:00.000000000Z", "close_reason": "Python wrapper mirroring nx", "source_repo": ".", "compaction_level": 0, "original_size": 0}
+{"id": "franken_networkx-bipartiteattr", "title": "REVIEW: [HIGH] complete_bipartite_graph omitted per-node 'bipartite' attribute + graph name", "description": "nx.complete_bipartite_graph tags the first partition's nodes with ``bipartite=0`` and the second partition's with ``bipartite=1``, and sets ``G.graph['name']='complete_bipartite_graph(n1, n2)'``. These are the protocol keys that nx.algorithms.bipartite consumes to pick a side; without them, downstream bipartite algorithms fall back to heuristics and can produce wrong partitions. The Rust fast path (invoked for integer n1,n2) produced none of these attributes. Always take the Python path so ``bipartite`` + name match nx exactly.", "status": "closed", "priority": 2, "issue_type": "bug", "created_at": "2026-04-24T14:45:00.000000000Z", "created_by": "cc-networkx", "updated_at": "2026-04-24T14:45:00.000000000Z", "closed_at": "2026-04-24T14:45:00.000000000Z", "close_reason": "Drop Rust fast path; Python fallback sets attrs", "source_repo": ".", "compaction_level": 0, "original_size": 0}
+{"id": "franken_networkx-sbmrng", "title": "REVIEW: [HIGH] stochastic_block_model produced different edge sets than nx for same (sizes, p, seed)", "description": "Both fnx's Rust fast path and its Python fallback diverged structurally from nx. On sizes=[3,3] p=[[0.5,0.1],[0.1,0.5]] seed=42 the Rust path gave 2 edges; the Python path gave 5 edges; nx gave 8 edges. nx's sparse-mode sampling uses geometric-skip sampling (log_random / log(1-p) floor) iterated per block pair via combinations_with_replacement, which consumes seed.random() in a specific pattern; fnx's per-node-pair loop consumed seed.random() in a different order. Validate inputs locally with nx's exact messages, then delegate generation to nx and rebuild as an fnx Graph/DiGraph. Verified edge-for-edge parity across sizes [3,3],[5,5,5],[2,2],[10] with various seeds, plus directed mode.", "status": "closed", "priority": 2, "issue_type": "bug", "created_at": "2026-04-24T14:45:00.000000000Z", "created_by": "cc-networkx", "updated_at": "2026-04-24T14:45:00.000000000Z", "closed_at": "2026-04-24T14:45:00.000000000Z", "close_reason": "Delegate to nx; local validation preserved", "source_repo": ".", "compaction_level": 0, "original_size": 0}
